<subSubSection id="D4E0654CFFFCFD05FF7008FCB04FFF00" box="[151,611,186,212]" pageId="10" pageNumber="57" type="description">
<paragraph id="9C4536C7FFFCFD05FF7008FCB04FFF00" blockId="10.[151,611,151,212]" box="[151,611,186,212]" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">
(
<figureCitation id="04C12A42FFFCFD05FF7808FCB2DDFF00" box="[159,241,186,212]" captionStart="PLATE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,238,1874,1898]" captionTargetBox="[227,1352,205,1841]" captionTargetId="figure-85@3.[215,1357,197,1841]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="PLATE 1 (haenschi and sophorae) 1. Brassolis haenschi haenschi female ECUADOR: Normandia, BMNH. 2. Brassolis haenschi haenschi male ECUADOR: Macas ZMUC. 3. Brassolis sophorae luridus Holotype male, COLOMBIA: Río Magdalena, BMNH. 4. Brassolis sophorae philomela Paralectotype female, ECUADOR: Macas, BMNH. 5. Brassolis sophorae philomela Lectotype male, ECUADOR: Macas, BMNH. 6. Brassolis sophorae ardens female, Peru La Union, BMNH. 7. Brassolis sophorae ardens Lectotype male, PERU: Pozuzo, BMNH." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5125053" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5125053/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">Plate 1</figureCitation>
, figs. 1&amp;2; 
<figureCitation id="04C12A42FFFCFD05FE9908FCB3FCFF00" box="[382,464,186,212]" captionStart="PLATE 3" captionStartId="9.[151,238,1768,1792]" captionTargetBox="[226,1360,194,1740]" captionTargetId="figure-116@9.[226,1360,194,1740]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="PLATE 3 (details). 1,2. Brassolis granadensis female, COLOMBIA: Otanche, JFL. 3. Brassolis granadensis male, COLOMBIA: Río Magdalena, BMNH. 4,5. Brassolis isthmia isthmia female, PANAMÁ: Taboga Island, BMNH. 6. Brassolis isthmia isthmia Lectotype male, PANAMÁ: Lion Hill, BMNH. 7,8. Brassolis isthmia daisye Paratype female, COLOMBIA: Chaparral, ICNO. 9. Brassolis isthmia daisye Paratype male, COLOMBIA: Mariquita, UPI. 10,11. Brassolis isthmia wallengreni Paratype female, ECUADOR: Tinalandia, CRB. 12. Brassolis isthmia wallengreni Paratype male, ECUADOR: Balzapamba (Paralectotype male of Brassolis granadensis), BMNH. 13. Brassolis haenschi haenschi male ECUADOR: Macas, ZMUC. 14. Brassolis haenschi haenschi male ECUADOR: Macas, ZMUC. 15. Brassolis haenschi haenschi male ECUADOR: Macas, ZMUC." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5125059" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5125059/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">Plate 3</figureCitation>
, figs 13–15)
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="D4E0654CFFFCFD05FF70094CB1A3FCD7" pageId="10" pageNumber="57" type="reference_group">
<paragraph id="9C4536C7FFFCFD05FF70094CB76EFE10" blockId="10.[151,1437,266,1092]" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">
<taxonomicName id="5BFA4D44FFFCFD05FF70094CB35BFEF7" authorityName="Stichel. The" authorityYear="1902" box="[151,375,266,291]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Brassolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="haenschi">
<emphasis id="AE8EEAD5FFFCFD05FF70094CB35BFEF7" box="[151,375,266,291]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">Brassolis haenschi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a rare, high-altitude (
<quantity id="5B029B22FFFCFD05FD42094CB11BFEF0" box="[677,823,266,292]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.45" metricValueMax="2.0" metricValueMin="0.9" pageId="10" pageNumber="57" unit="m" value="1450.0" valueMax="2000.0" valueMin="900.0">900–2000m</quantity>
), species known so far only in the central eastern Andes in 
<collectingCountry id="E4ED7657FFFCFD05FEEB0974B341FE98" box="[268,365,306,332]" name="Ecuador" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">Ecuador</collectingCountry>
(nominate 
<taxonomicName id="5BFA4D44FFFCFD05FE100974B073FE9F" authorityName="Stichel. The" authorityYear="1902" box="[503,607,306,331]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Brassolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="haenschi">
<emphasis id="AE8EEAD5FFFCFD05FE100974B073FE9F" box="[503,607,306,331]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">haenschi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), central 
<collectingCountry id="E4ED7657FFFCFD05FD340974B125FE98" box="[723,777,306,332]" name="Peru" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">Peru</collectingCountry>
(
<emphasis id="AE8EEAD5FFFCFD05FCFB0974B107FE9F" box="[796,811,306,331]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">h</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="AE8EEAD5FFFCFD05FCDB0974B187FE9F" box="[828,939,306,331]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">rufescens</emphasis>
Rothschild) and 
<collectingCountry id="E4ED7657FFFCFD05FB9D0974B6DEFE98" box="[1146,1266,306,332]" name="Venezuela" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">Venezuela</collectingCountry>
(
<emphasis id="AE8EEAD5FFFCFD05FAE20974B7B0FE9F" box="[1285,1436,306,331]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">h. maritimus</emphasis>
Stichel). At times, all three taxa have been regarded as subspecies of 
<taxonomicName id="5BFA4D44FFFCFD05FC5D091CB69CFEA0" authority="Godart [1824]" authorityName="Godart" authorityYear="1824" box="[954,1200,346,372]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Brassolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="astyra">
<emphasis id="AE8EEAD5FFFCFD05FC5D091CB62FFEA7" box="[954,1027,346,371]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">astyra</emphasis>
Godart [1824]
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="F86B4B36FFFCFD05FB58091CB7BBFEA0" author="Fruhstorfer, H." box="[1215,1431,346,372]" pageId="10" pageNumber="57" pagination="285 - 332" refId="ref5981" refString="Fruhstorfer, H. (1912 b) Family Brassolidae. Pages 285 - 332 In: Seitz A. (ed.), The Macrolepidoptera of the World, vol. 2. Stuttgart: Alfred Kernen Verlag." type="book chapter" year="1912">Fruhstorfer 1912b</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="F86B4B36FFFCFD05FF7009C4B377FE48" author="Rothschild, L. W." box="[151,347,386,412]" pageId="10" pageNumber="57" pagination="299 - 318" refId="ref6053" refString="Rothschild, L. W. (1916) Notes on Amathusiidae, Brassolidae, Morphidae, etc, with descriptions of new forms. Novitates Zoologicae, 23, 299 - 318." type="journal article" year="1916">Rothschild 1916</bibRefCitation>
) or even 
<taxonomicName id="5BFA4D44FFFCFD05FE2A09C4B1A1FE48" authority="(Racheli and Racheli 2001)" baseAuthorityName="Racheli and Racheli" baseAuthorityYear="2001" box="[461,909,386,412]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Brassolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sophorae">
<emphasis id="AE8EEAD5FFFCFD05FE2A09C4B016FE4F" box="[461,570,386,411]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">sophorae</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="F86B4B36FFFCFD05FDAC09C4B1A8FE48" author="Racheli, R. &amp; Racheli, T." box="[587,900,386,412]" pageId="10" pageNumber="57" pagination="213 - 380" refId="ref6022" refString="Racheli, R. &amp; Racheli, T. (2001) An annotated list of Ecuadorian butterflies. Fragmenta entomologica (Rome), 33, 213 - 380." type="journal article" year="2001">Racheli and Racheli 2001</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. Carla Penz (
<emphasis id="AE8EEAD5FFFCFD05FBC909C4B6E1FE4F" box="[1070,1229,386,411]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">pers. commn.</emphasis>
) informs me that the male genitalia of 
<taxonomicName id="5BFA4D44FFFCFD05FE6909ECB3DAFE17" authorityName="Stichel. The" authorityYear="1902" box="[398,502,426,451]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Brassolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="haenschi">
<emphasis id="AE8EEAD5FFFCFD05FE6909ECB3DAFE17" box="[398,502,426,451]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">haenschi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(and 
<taxonomicName id="5BFA4D44FFFCFD05FDDE09ECB0AEFE17" authorityName="Godart" authorityYear="1824" box="[569,642,426,451]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Brassolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="astyra">
<emphasis id="AE8EEAD5FFFCFD05FDDE09ECB0AEFE17" box="[569,642,426,451]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">astyra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) show a few, slight, differences from 
<taxonomicName id="5BFA4D44FFFCFD05FBD909ECB687FE17" baseAuthorityName="Racheli and Racheli" baseAuthorityYear="2001" box="[1086,1195,426,451]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Brassolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sophorae">
<emphasis id="AE8EEAD5FFFCFD05FBD909ECB687FE17" box="[1086,1195,426,451]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">sophorae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="5BFA4D44FFFCFD05FB0309ECB716FE17" authorityName="Bates" authorityYear="1864" box="[1252,1338,426,451]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Brassolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="isthmia">
<emphasis id="AE8EEAD5FFFCFD05FB0309ECB716FE17" box="[1252,1338,426,451]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">isthmia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9C4536C7FFFCFD05FF210994B1A3FCD7" blockId="10.[151,1437,266,1092]" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">
Male 
<taxonomicName id="5BFA4D44FFFCFD05FEEE0994B35DFE3F" authorityName="Stichel. The" authorityYear="1902" box="[265,369,466,491]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Brassolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="haenschi">
<emphasis id="AE8EEAD5FFFCFD05FEEE0994B35DFE3F" box="[265,369,466,491]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">haenschi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar to both 
<taxonomicName id="5BFA4D44FFFCFD05FDA40994B0B5FE3F" authorityName="Bates" authorityYear="1864" box="[579,665,466,491]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Brassolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="isthmia">
<emphasis id="AE8EEAD5FFFCFD05FDA40994B0B5FE3F" box="[579,665,466,491]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">isthmia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="5BFA4D44FFFCFD05FD360994B112FE3F" baseAuthorityName="Racheli and Racheli" baseAuthorityYear="2001" box="[721,830,466,491]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Brassolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sophorae">
<emphasis id="AE8EEAD5FFFCFD05FD360994B112FE3F" box="[721,830,466,491]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">sophorae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The main difference from these taxa is in the ocelli on the hindwing underside (particularly the lower one). In both sexes of the three 
<taxonomicName id="5BFA4D44FFFCFD05FB9B09BCB6C8FDC7" authorityName="Stichel. The" authorityYear="1902" box="[1148,1252,506,531]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Brassolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="haenschi">
<emphasis id="AE8EEAD5FFFCFD05FB9B09BCB6C8FDC7" box="[1148,1252,506,531]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">haenschi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
taxa examined (
<emphasis id="AE8EEAD5FFFCFD05FF460A64B33CFDEF" box="[161,272,546,571]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">rufescens</emphasis>
from 
<collectingCountry id="E4ED7657FFFCFD05FEBF0A64B3BDFDE8" box="[344,401,546,572]" name="Peru" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">Peru</collectingCountry>
, nominate 
<taxonomicName id="5BFA4D44FFFCFD05FDF40A64B057FDEF" authorityName="Stichel. The" authorityYear="1902" box="[531,635,546,571]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Brassolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="haenschi">
<emphasis id="AE8EEAD5FFFCFD05FDF40A64B057FDEF" box="[531,635,546,571]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">haenschi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry id="E4ED7657FFFCFD05FD230A64B10BFDE8" box="[708,807,546,572]" name="Ecuador" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">Ecuador</collectingCountry>
, and 
<emphasis id="AE8EEAD5FFFCFD05FC810A64B1F1FDEF" box="[870,989,546,571]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">maritimus</emphasis>
from 
<collectingCountry id="E4ED7657FFFCFD05FBC00A64B688FDE8" box="[1063,1188,546,572]" name="Venezuela" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">Venezuela</collectingCountry>
), the hindwing ocelli lack the narrow, dark brown, border seen in 
<taxonomicName id="5BFA4D44FFFCFD05FD4D0A0CB12CFDB7" authorityName="Bates" authorityYear="1864" box="[682,768,586,611]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Brassolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="isthmia">
<emphasis id="AE8EEAD5FFFCFD05FD4D0A0CB12CFDB7" box="[682,768,586,611]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">isthmia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<emphasis id="AE8EEAD5FFFCFD05FCDB0A0CB19DFDB7" box="[828,945,586,611]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">
<taxonomicName id="5BFA4D44FFFCFD05FCDB0A0CB181FDB7" baseAuthorityName="Racheli and Racheli" baseAuthorityYear="2001" box="[828,941,586,611]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Brassolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sophorae">sophorae</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
Additionally, on the forewing underside, the two very narrow submarginal bands which occur in 
<taxonomicName id="5BFA4D44FFFCFD05FCC70A34B15AFD5F" authorityName="Bates" authorityYear="1864" box="[800,886,626,651]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Brassolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="isthmia">
<emphasis id="AE8EEAD5FFFCFD05FCC70A34B15AFD5F" box="[800,886,626,651]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">isthmia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(very clear on 
<figureCitation id="04C12A42FFFCFD05FBC10A34B654FD58" box="[1062,1144,626,652]" captionStart="PLATE 3" captionStartId="9.[151,238,1768,1792]" captionTargetBox="[226,1360,194,1740]" captionTargetId="figure-116@9.[226,1360,194,1740]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="PLATE 3 (details). 1,2. Brassolis granadensis female, COLOMBIA: Otanche, JFL. 3. Brassolis granadensis male, COLOMBIA: Río Magdalena, BMNH. 4,5. Brassolis isthmia isthmia female, PANAMÁ: Taboga Island, BMNH. 6. Brassolis isthmia isthmia Lectotype male, PANAMÁ: Lion Hill, BMNH. 7,8. Brassolis isthmia daisye Paratype female, COLOMBIA: Chaparral, ICNO. 9. Brassolis isthmia daisye Paratype male, COLOMBIA: Mariquita, UPI. 10,11. Brassolis isthmia wallengreni Paratype female, ECUADOR: Tinalandia, CRB. 12. Brassolis isthmia wallengreni Paratype male, ECUADOR: Balzapamba (Paralectotype male of Brassolis granadensis), BMNH. 13. Brassolis haenschi haenschi male ECUADOR: Macas, ZMUC. 14. Brassolis haenschi haenschi male ECUADOR: Macas, ZMUC. 15. Brassolis haenschi haenschi male ECUADOR: Macas, ZMUC." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5125059" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5125059/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">Plate 3</figureCitation>
, fig. 4) and 
<taxonomicName id="5BFA4D44FFFCFD05FAE30A34B75DFD5F" baseAuthorityName="Racheli and Racheli" baseAuthorityYear="2001" box="[1284,1393,626,651]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Brassolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sophorae">
<emphasis id="AE8EEAD5FFFCFD05FAE30A34B75DFD5F" box="[1284,1393,626,651]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">sophorae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are either absent (as in all nominate 
<taxonomicName id="5BFA4D44FFFCFD05FDF40ADCB057FD67" authorityName="Stichel. The" authorityYear="1902" box="[531,635,666,691]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Brassolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="haenschi">
<emphasis id="AE8EEAD5FFFCFD05FDF40ADCB057FD67" box="[531,635,666,691]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">haenschi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
examined), or represented by just one (never two) indistinct line (as in a female 
<emphasis id="AE8EEAD5FFFCFD05FECD0A84B3B5FD0F" box="[298,409,706,731]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">rufescens</emphasis>
from Huancabamba and 
<specimenCount id="8AFCFD4EFFFCFD05FD2A0A84B117FD08" box="[717,827,706,732]" pageId="10" pageNumber="57" type="male">one male</specimenCount>
<emphasis id="AE8EEAD5FFFCFD05FCA20A84B190FD0F" box="[837,956,706,731]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">maritimus</emphasis>
from 
<collectingCountry id="E4ED7657FFFCFD05FBED0A84B6A4FD08" box="[1034,1160,706,732]" name="Venezuela" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">Venezuela</collectingCountry>
). These two characters appear to be defining features of 
<taxonomicName id="5BFA4D44FFFCFD05FDFD0AACB0AEFCD7" authorityName="Stichel. The" authorityYear="1902" box="[538,642,746,771]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Brassolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="haenschi">
<emphasis id="AE8EEAD5FFFCFD05FDFD0AACB0AEFCD7" box="[538,642,746,771]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">haenschi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="04C12A42FFFCFD05FD760AACB0C9FCD0" box="[657,741,746,772]" captionStart="PLATE 3" captionStartId="9.[151,238,1768,1792]" captionTargetBox="[226,1360,194,1740]" captionTargetId="figure-116@9.[226,1360,194,1740]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="PLATE 3 (details). 1,2. Brassolis granadensis female, COLOMBIA: Otanche, JFL. 3. Brassolis granadensis male, COLOMBIA: Río Magdalena, BMNH. 4,5. Brassolis isthmia isthmia female, PANAMÁ: Taboga Island, BMNH. 6. Brassolis isthmia isthmia Lectotype male, PANAMÁ: Lion Hill, BMNH. 7,8. Brassolis isthmia daisye Paratype female, COLOMBIA: Chaparral, ICNO. 9. Brassolis isthmia daisye Paratype male, COLOMBIA: Mariquita, UPI. 10,11. Brassolis isthmia wallengreni Paratype female, ECUADOR: Tinalandia, CRB. 12. Brassolis isthmia wallengreni Paratype male, ECUADOR: Balzapamba (Paralectotype male of Brassolis granadensis), BMNH. 13. Brassolis haenschi haenschi male ECUADOR: Macas, ZMUC. 14. Brassolis haenschi haenschi male ECUADOR: Macas, ZMUC. 15. Brassolis haenschi haenschi male ECUADOR: Macas, ZMUC." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5125059" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5125059/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">Plate 3</figureCitation>
, figs. 13&amp;14).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="D4E0654CFFFCFD05FF210B54B6FFFB90" pageId="10" pageNumber="57" type="description">
<paragraph id="9C4536C7FFFCFD05FF210B54B71EFC18" blockId="10.[151,1437,266,1092]" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">
The forewing band of nominate 
<taxonomicName id="5BFA4D44FFFCFD05FDA50B54B086FCFF" authorityName="Stichel. The" authorityYear="1902" box="[578,682,786,811]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Brassolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="haenschi">
<emphasis id="AE8EEAD5FFFCFD05FDA50B54B086FCFF" box="[578,682,786,811]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">haenschi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has an almost white ‘highlight’ close to the cell and costal margin (
<figureCitation id="04C12A42FFFCFD05FF2C0B7CB333FC80" box="[203,287,826,852]" captionStart="PLATE 3" captionStartId="9.[151,238,1768,1792]" captionTargetBox="[226,1360,194,1740]" captionTargetId="figure-116@9.[226,1360,194,1740]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="PLATE 3 (details). 1,2. Brassolis granadensis female, COLOMBIA: Otanche, JFL. 3. Brassolis granadensis male, COLOMBIA: Río Magdalena, BMNH. 4,5. Brassolis isthmia isthmia female, PANAMÁ: Taboga Island, BMNH. 6. Brassolis isthmia isthmia Lectotype male, PANAMÁ: Lion Hill, BMNH. 7,8. Brassolis isthmia daisye Paratype female, COLOMBIA: Chaparral, ICNO. 9. Brassolis isthmia daisye Paratype male, COLOMBIA: Mariquita, UPI. 10,11. Brassolis isthmia wallengreni Paratype female, ECUADOR: Tinalandia, CRB. 12. Brassolis isthmia wallengreni Paratype male, ECUADOR: Balzapamba (Paralectotype male of Brassolis granadensis), BMNH. 13. Brassolis haenschi haenschi male ECUADOR: Macas, ZMUC. 14. Brassolis haenschi haenschi male ECUADOR: Macas, ZMUC. 15. Brassolis haenschi haenschi male ECUADOR: Macas, ZMUC." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5125059" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5125059/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">Plate 3</figureCitation>
, fig. 15); on the hindwing, there is just a very faint, apically developed, sub-marginal band. In the female, there is no sub-marginal hindwing band; the forewing band is a deep orange and composed of a series of touching spots. Where these cross the upper part of the cell, they are elongated distally into ‘flame-like’ spots. On the underside, the outer ocellus on the hindwing does not have an inner, dark brown circle.
</paragraph>
